00:08:59.920 --> 00:09:01.320
Let me see.

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:02.500
Awesome.

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:06.120
However, there is a
problem with brainstorming.

00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:09.030
And a lot of people
have practiced it

00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:12.490
without actually knowing
why certain things are

00:09:12.490 --> 00:09:14.760
done in a certain way
and, as a result of that,

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:17.010
may actually be
doing it incorrectly.

00:09:17.010 --> 00:09:19.650
We have an excerpt
of an article--

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:22.160
I'm sorry-- a chapter
from a book called,

00:09:22.160 --> 00:09:24.762
Applied Imagination, which
is written by Alex Osborn.

00:09:24.762 --> 00:09:26.220
This is a guy who
actually came out

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:28.960
with the term brainstorming
and the practice of it.

00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:30.560
He worked in advertising.

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:36.200
And he has lamented
since he wrote that book

00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:37.685
that a lot of
people kind of liked

00:09:37.685 --> 00:09:40.060
the output of brainstorming,
but didn't really understand

00:09:40.060 --> 00:09:41.450
the practice of it.

00:09:41.450 --> 00:09:44.290
So I'm going to try to
start from first principles

00:09:44.290 --> 00:09:46.100
so that you understand
why brainstorming is

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:48.130
and how it's supposed
to be working.

00:09:48.130 --> 00:09:51.870
And hopefully, you can sort
of get the benefits of it,

00:09:51.870 --> 00:09:57.420
without maybe, say,
overstating its power.

00:09:57.420 --> 00:10:00.740
Now, the main reason why we're
doing brainstorming in groups--

00:10:00.740 --> 00:10:03.369
you will hear people out there
in the game industry saying

00:10:03.369 --> 00:10:05.160
that brainstorming's
not necessarily always

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:08.940
the best way to be able to come
up with an idea for a game.

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:11.630
However, in this
class in particular

00:10:11.630 --> 00:10:14.830
and in a lot of video game
design outside of this class,

00:10:14.830 --> 00:10:18.450
game design is coordinated,
creative collaboration

00:10:18.450 --> 00:10:20.620
involving different
skilled workers.

00:10:20.620 --> 00:10:22.980
And if this is going to
be the first time you're

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:24.790
going to work with
a team, you need

00:10:24.790 --> 00:10:28.130
to understand who are the people
who you might be working with.

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:30.660
Brainstorming, if nothing else,
can be a really, really good

00:10:30.660 --> 00:10:32.850
way to just be able to get a
sense of who it is that you're

00:10:32.850 --> 00:10:33.960
going to be working with.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:36.484
And when we start
forming up teams,

00:10:36.484 --> 00:10:37.900
you're not going
to necessarily be

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:40.440
able to choose who you're
brainstorming with.

00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:44.620
So you want to be able to get
a quick read of their ideas

00:10:44.620 --> 00:10:46.850
and what their interests
are and maybe decide,

00:10:46.850 --> 00:10:50.700
hey, this is a person I'm going
to do Project 1 with later on.

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:53.180
However, there are very
strong social pressures

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:58.490
of being imaginative in a
collaborative environment,

00:10:58.490 --> 00:11:01.560
especially here in MIT.

00:11:01.560 --> 00:11:04.760
There's a lot of pressure
to hold back your ideas

00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:07.990
or maybe not say what's
coming to your mind

00:11:07.990 --> 00:11:09.794
because you think
that's kind of dumb,

00:11:09.794 --> 00:11:11.960
but other people are going
to think that I'm stupid,

00:11:11.960 --> 00:11:12.986
or anything like that.

00:11:12.986 --> 00:11:14.610
And brainstorming
has certain practices

00:11:14.610 --> 00:11:16.700
to be able to get you past that.

00:11:16.700 --> 00:11:18.800
So there are four
principles of brainstorming.

